76561198353187264,Not Recommended,252530,30480791,Posted: 12 March,all,troyski72,"This review is quite in depth, so here is the summarisation, but for some who are new or want the in depth review, please see below.OMSI 2: 6/10 or 64%. Would recommend to the right person, but overall I can't, as base price is way to high as well as the several add-ons. You have to invest yourself into the game almost as much as me, to get some fun out of it.Personally I find it to be fine.-Quick NotesThis game is a massive mix of the good and the bad, as many negatives, link to positives. If you read on, it will make more sense... and just to summarise, despite what is seen below, I recommend this game, but only to hard core simulation fans.I'm not just going to pour out the negatives, as I've been playing this for hundreds of hours, so I'll get the good stuff out first and I only have the X10 and Three Generations addons, so the positives and negatives only reflect them.-The Actual Review1. The BusesThe buses that come with the base game, the MAN SD200, SD202, NL202 & NG272 (I think its called that) are well made and rarely have any issues. They're fun to drive and smooth, with the exclusion of the NL202 (partially) the NG272.(see negatives below)The X10 Addon bus, the MAN Lion's City DD (AKA DL05, 07,08 & 09) are well made too.2. The WorldsThe base Spandau map, is distinct and well created, with rarely any glitches, but it does lead to an issue.Berlin in the X10 Addon takes place primarily in the south west of Berlin, with the famous Berlin Zoo and the town of Zehlendorf being immersive and well made.3. The CommunityEver since the original was released in 2011, many players of OMSI have made add on buses, maps, repaints and more for free, which really has increased the longevity of the game and has allowed OMSI players other the world to come together. Not to sound flowery, but its nice to see others adding content to the game based on their hometown, so there is a varying degree of maps and buses to utilise and explore. Again, there are negatives to this.4. The Game's ExisitenceThe game existing is a good thing, due to the lack of well made bus simulators, which this definitely is. Amongst older simulators like the Bus Simulator series and even the really old Bus Driver from SCS software, it stacks up pretty well.Whilst, yet again, this is a good thing, it leads to an negative.1. The BusesSMALLER ISSUESAs stated before with the NL202, there is a tiny nitpick and this can also be stated for the 'Three Generations' addon of the 2013 Citaro C2 bus.The braking is quite tight, even if you don't apply too much pressure, which can lead to passengers complaining. adn on the C2 bus, a jerky ride. The NG272 has a larger problem. I understand the point of the swaying connector of the bus, hence the 'articulated' name, but the squeaking noise it makes when turning corners can be quite annoying, especially on the more corner heavy route: the 5 (or 130).The Lion's City DD can also have texture errors, as the bus is quite demanding, meaning that sometmes textures don't load, leaving the windows opaque, preventing anything to be seen from the inside.BIGGER ISSUESThe more prevalent negative however, is the fact the range of buses is quite poor for both the base game and the X10 addon. Only 2 double deckers with slight variations and 1 single and articulated bus for the base game, as well as only 1 single decker for the X10 addon. Its pretty poor, which leads to many (me as an example) paying for addon buses to use in the maps.2. The WorldsBASE SPANDAU MAPI appreciate the effort placed into recreating many cities around the world for players to explore, but in the long run, these efforts will be forgotton and people will wonder why there isn't more.For example, the base Spandau map in all honesty has only 2 day routes: the 5 and 92.I don't count the 130 and 137, just because they take place in a different time period, its essentially the same as the original, except for the extension of the 137 form Freudstr. to Falkensee Bahnhof.I'm sure players have seen the AI routes like the 13, 54, 94 and 97 routes (for example) and though why they aren't fully playable. I don't see why a revisit to these routes to extend them to their actual destinations would not be considered.To make it a free or even a £5 at most fee would be great and would leave the map feeling more complete and open world. This is a feature that more average gamers to the genre will likely find an annoyance, and drops its recommendation value quite low.X10 ADDONI don't have every DLC, but I know the same can be said for the X10 Addon, as only 2 Berlin buses (the 115 and X10 are full routes)  and 2 routes (I think the 626 and another route) in Teltow ( a town in the Brandenburg area (or county as I'd relate it to) is fully playable.Lots of routes like the 110, 285, 601/X1, 621, 623 & 625 buses are only partially playable and it can be quite blatant.For example, the 285 travels from Dahlem Waldfriedhof to S+U Rathaus Steglitz in real life and the destination blinds even state Steglitz, but (and this is especially apparent when selecting the Appenzeller terminus, as the same thing happens) the route ends abruptly ends on a road called Wupperstr. in Zehlendorf, making the route quite short, shorter than the 5 or 92 from the Spandau map.This is a let down, as the route tends to use a double decker from time to time and using it can seem unnessecary depending on the time of day and amount of passengers spawned in the world.Despite the long paragraph detailing the 285, this occurs with the 110, which is almost criminally poor in how the route's terminus (Grunewald Roseneck) is a lie, as you see it at its real terminue (U Oskar Helene Heim) when driving commonly the 285, but possibly the 115, 623 and X10. But I'll leave it at that.3. The Community-TO BE CLEARThe community isn't the issue, but they are used by the developers, to create less add- on content, or relieve the feeling of leaving consumers underwhelmed, with the high price to pay for so little. The communities and their products to average consumers can be a minefield to understand, as downloading and learning where to store add on buses can be a cinch, but downloading maps and some repaints can be hard to understand and find out where to place them, leaving the consumer alienated and helpless. Believe me, this has happened to me and its not usually creator's fault, as they try to explain what to do for installations, but sometimes their native language is different.-BUSESThe various communities have varying buses with varying quality. Some can be excellent amd some can be poor. I've come across a few which fail to work normally, or have a slight issue that can't be resolved, which again, makes things tough for the consumers. The lack of double deckers, is quite apparent, as the only double decker fan made bus, is a Lion's City DD, that has a few issues, but an official version, as mentioned before, can be used with the X10 pack. Single deckers make up around 80% of the fan buses, which can be an issue to those who wish to drive a new or different double decker on a longer, busier route. Articulated buses are fine, but tend to be less reliable with high density passengers than double deckers.-MAPSFans have gone as far to recreate Spandau in a fictional and interesting way, (New Berlin- Spandau Map) as it utilises the many AI routes, but completely change the routes for some, which can be seen as a positive or negative. Assets have had to be reused from the original map, which is noticable sometimes, but is acceptable. The map however, for me at least rarely works and the text of issues relating to the map and any others that occur, tend to be in German, so English and other language speakers will have an annoying time tryong to figure and work it out.As stated before, maps can be a hassle to implement into the game's files.Seems I've reached the text limit."
